Q1. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S18Q1)

  • A. Tundra
  • B. Taiga
  • C. Temperate rainforest
  • D. Savanna
Q2. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S18Q2)
Which of the following best describes the photic zone in an aquatic biome?
  • A. The deepest part of the ocean where light cannot penetrate.
  • B. The upper layer of water where sunlight penetrates, allowing for photosynthesis.
  • C. The bottom sediment layer of a lake or ocean.
  • D. The intertidal zone where land and water meet.

  • A. Ocean salinity
  • B. Atmospheric nitrogen levels
  • C. Difference in carbon dioxide concentration
  • D. Depth of the ocean current

  • A. Nitrification
  • B. Denitrification
  • C. Nitrogen fixation
  • D. Assimilation

Q6. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S18Q6)

  • A. Precipitation
  • B. Transpiration
  • C. Evaporation
  • D. Condensation
Q7. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S18Q7)
Which of the following best defines gross primary productivity (GPP)?
  • A. The amount of energy left over after producers have met their own energetic needs.
  • B. The rate at which biomass accumulates in an ecosystem.
  • C. The total rate at which solar energy is converted into organic compounds by producers.
  • D. The energy transferred to the next trophic level.
Q8. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S18Q8)
In most ecosystems, what happens to the majority of energy that is transferred from one trophic level to the next?
  • A. It is stored as biomass in the consumer.
  • B. It is passed on to the subsequent trophic level.
  • C. It is recycled back to the producers.
  • D. It is lost as heat during metabolic processes.
Q9. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S18Q9)
If a primary producer level in an ecosystem contains $10,000$ kcal of energy, and assuming a $10\%$ energy transfer efficiency, how much energy would be available to a tertiary consumer?
  • A. $1000$ kcal
  • B. $100$ kcal
  • C. $10$ kcal
  • D. $1$ kcal

  • A. Commensalism
  • B. Parasitism
  • C. Mutualism
  • D. Predation
Q11. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S18Q11)

  • B. Ocean absorption of $CO_2$
  • C. Burning of fossil fuels
  • D. Formation of limestone

How does the process of denitrification impact the global nitrogen cycle?
  • A. It converts atmospheric nitrogen into a usable form for plants.
  • B. It makes nitrogen available in aquatic ecosystems through runoff.
  • C. It transforms ammonia into nitrites and nitrates.
  • D. It returns nitrogen gas to the atmosphere, completing the cycle.

  • A. Denitrification
  • B. Weathering
  • C. Photosynthesis
  • D. Respiration
Q14. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S18Q14)
An ecosystem has $50,000$ joules of energy at the primary producer level. If the energy transfer efficiency is $10\%$ between trophic levels, and primary consumers lose $90\%$ of the transferred energy to respiration and waste, how much energy is assimilated by the secondary consumers?
  • A. $5000$ J
  • B. $500$ J
  • C. $450$ J
  • D. $50$ J
Q15. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S18Q15)
Which of the following represents a significant anthropogenic source of carbon dioxide ($CO_2$) to the atmosphere, accelerating the carbon cycle?
  • A. Photosynthesis by marine algae
  • B. Volcanic eruptions
  • C. Deforestation and burning of biomass
  • D. Weathering of carbonate rocks
Q16. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S18Q16)
Eutrophication, often caused by runoff of excess nutrients, is primarily associated with an overload of which biogeochemical cycle?
  • A. Carbon cycle
  • B. Nitrogen cycle
  • C. Hydrologic cycle
  • D. Phosphorus cycle
Q17. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S18Q17)
Unlike the carbon and nitrogen cycles, the phosphorus cycle does not have a significant atmospheric gaseous phase. What is the main implication of this difference?
  • A. Phosphorus is more readily available to terrestrial plants.
  • B. Phosphorus is rapidly cycled through the atmosphere globally.
  • C. The movement of phosphorus is much slower and primarily confined to water and land.
  • D. Phosphorus is quickly lost from ecosystems through evaporation.
Q18. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S18Q18)
What is the primary role of decomposers in an ecosystem?
  • A. To produce their own food through photosynthesis.
  • B. To consume other organisms for energy.
  • C. To break down dead organic matter and return nutrients to the soil.
  • D. To regulate atmospheric gas concentrations.
Q19. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S18Q19)
An area of tropical rainforest has a net primary productivity (NPP) of $2.5$ kg $C/m^2/year$. If this rainforest covers $100$ $km^2$, how much carbon is stored in the net biomass produced annually by the producers in this area? (Note: $1$ km = $1000$ m)
  • A. $2.5 \times 10^3$ kg C
  • B. $2.5 \times 10^8$ kg C
  • C. $2.5 \times 10^9$ kg C
  • D. $2.5 \times 10^6$ kg C
Q20. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S18Q20)
Which of the following best describes how the availability of resources influences species interactions within an ecosystem?
  • A. A: High resource availability primarily leads to increased competition among species.
  • B. B: Limited resource availability often intensifies competition among species for those resources.
  • C. C: Resource availability has no significant impact on predator-prey dynamics, only on symbiotic relationships.
  • D. D: The amount of available resources solely determines the carrying capacity, not the type of species interactions.

If this energy is transferred through three successive trophic levels (primary consumers, secondary consumers, and tertiary consumers), how much energy would typically be available to the tertiary consumers, assuming the $10\%$ rule of energy transfer?
  • A. A: $100 \text{ kcal}$
  • B. B: $1,000 \text{ kcal}$
  • C. C: $10,000 \text{ kcal}$
  • D. D: $100,000 \text{ kcal}$

  • B. B: By converting solar energy into chemical energy through the process of photosynthesis.
  • C. C: By absorbing heat energy directly from their surrounding environment.
